{"_id":"K2jgWwBS2qWKWAai","name":"Shrine Description & Layout","content":"<p>The road is still passing through dense woodland but there is a clear side-turning, with a large white boulder to mark it.</p>\n<p>On one side of the boulder is carved the symbol of Ulric; on the other is the symbol of Sigmar - or what remains of it. It is defaced, someone has scrawled 'remember Bosel' on it.</p>\n<p>Half a mile down the turning is an open area of flattish rocky ground, an acre or two across. In the middle of it is a simple yet elegant building. It is larger than a normal wayside shrine, and in fact not unlike the temples typically found in larger villages: about forty feet long, and rising at one end to a low tower. A river runs along one side of the area, and beyond it the forest continues. On the edge of the clearing, next to the river and about seventy yards from the shrine itself, is an￾other building: smaller, lower and more functional, with shut￾tered windows.</p>\n<h2>The Interior</h2>\n<p>The interior of the shrine is dominated by a long, thin outcrop of pale rock, which glitters and glistens in the light of two dozen large lamps that hang from the ceiling. The lamps’ brass bodies are marked with the alternating signs of the wolf ’s head and the twin-tailed comet, and the imagery of Sigmar and Ulric alternates in a similar fashion throughout.</p>\n<p>There are no pews or prayer-stools in the shrine: the floor is clean but completely bare. Any of the attending priests can explain that this is because the Sigmarite way is to stand or kneel on bare stone, so they did not require pews; the Ulricans, not wanting to appear softer or less devoted, also eschewed their customary use of pews.</p>\n<p>At the far end of the shrine, the ceiling rises in an octagonal tower. Beneath the centre of the tower is the highest part of the rock outcrop, which stands about3 ft above floor level. A sharp break indicates where, according to the legends of both faiths, the god snapped a piece off the outcrop to defend himself.</p>\n<p>An impressive statue of Ulric, depicted holding a shard of rock, stands against the back wall . As in most of Ulric’s temples, an eternal flame burns in a circular stone fire-pit in front of the statue. On entering the shrine, the sound of the flame flickering is audible, whilst the smell of the fire lingers and the temperature drops significantly.</p>\n<p>An altar to Sigmar stands in the south-eastern part of this area, positioned so that worshippers facing it are looking in the direction of Karaz-a-Karak, the Dwarven citadel where, it is believed, Sigmar went on his last journey as a mortal. This alignment is common in Sigmarite temples, especially older ones.</p>\n<p>Interior walls separate the public area of the shrine from two robing rooms: one for Sigmarite priests; the other for Ulrican priests. Beneath each is a small underground treasury, reached by a steep stone staircase under a trapdoor, where offerings and valuable ritual equipment are kept.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<h2>The Priests’ Quarters</h2>\n<p>This low, plain building accommodates the shrine’s complement of a dozen priests: six from each faith. Unusually, the Place of Shining Rock does not have any guest accommodation. Visitors are encouraged to pray in the shrine, leave a donation, and continue their journey. The priests have no objection to visitors pitching tents in the clearing for a night or two, but anyone planning on staying longer will arouse their suspicions. The shrine is a simple one, and there is nothing much to do here once one has prayed and donated.</p>\n<h3>The Hall</h3>\n<p>Double doors open onto a common hall and refectory. It is plainly furnished with two long, wooden tables flanked by benches.</p>\n<p>The room is so plain that it is austere and looks unfinished.</p>\n<p>Apart from a simple carved frieze around the top of the wall, decorated with alternating symbols of Ulric and Sigmar, everything is undecorated plaster and wood. A successful Charm Test may convince a Sigmarite priest to confess — privately, and not within the hearing of any other priest — that the lavish decoration found in other buildings associated with Sigmar’s worship has been neglected because the Sigmarites do not want to give the Ulricans any cause to echo the common northern sentiment that Reiklanders are all soft southern fops.</p>\n<p>An Ulrican priest, asked the same question, will reveal (again, privately) that the priests of the White Wolf are more than usually ascetic here, because they feel the need to represent northern toughness in front of the Sigmarites.</p>\n<h3>The Dormitories</h3>\n<p>To either side of the main hall is a door marked, respectively, with the hammer of Sigmar and the wolf ’s-head of Ulric. Each door leads to a dormitory accommodating six priests. These rooms are slightly more relaxed in their décor: the Ulrican dormitory is plain but comfortable; the Sigmarite counterpart is decorated tastefully, but not too lavishly.</p>\n<h3>The Kitchen and Stores</h3>\n<p>At the back of the main hall is a simple kitchen and store-room where meals are prepared and foodstuffs are stored.</p>","folder":"zhKNzx21YVsaN3CA","sort":0,"permission":{"default":0,"hNHeJbKl47AOkoOO":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"K55cGNapfz3Yrdo4","name":"Introduction","permission":{"default":0,"hNHeJbKl47AOkoOO":3},"folder":"ssJkbWra78rEQNX0","sort":200001,"flags":{},"content":"<p>Information:</p>\n<p>The Night Watch got a corpse at dawn, dumped it on the day watch.</p>\n<p>@JournalEntry[HMHG0ElZFJH400c8]{Erik Witzelheim} (a rat catcher) found the body in an alley near Rattelanger Durchgang.</p>\n<p>The body is at the Temple of Morr on @JournalEntry[o7Lpf6xyfxHgFdpB]{Toteninsel}.</p>\n<p>It has been identified as the body of Clemons Siberg, a senior clerk at the @JournalEntry[Pb40WlDPO8xjx9Ea]{The East Road Haulage Company}.</p>\n<p>Have his @JournalEntry[m8G5on6IFHozpY3s]{address} in Neuesgeldt.</p>"}
