{"_id":"nSp6Autp2kt3iV1r","name":"The Battle of Widow's Vale - 2508 IC","content":"<h1>The Battle of Widow's Vale</h1>\n<p>In 2508 IC, the Orc Warlord Ghizbak 'Eadbanger of the Red Maw Tribe succeeding in uniting the greenskin tribes of the southern Grey Mountains and lead them north into the area of Widow's Vale, sacking villages as they went.</p>\n<p>@JournalEntry[pZvoJAclOEdsJDV5]{Graf Sigismund von Jungfreud} issued a call to arms and rallied his vassals, including @JournalEntry[jkIGMtjPjrrtF3pK]{Graf Steirlich von Bruner}, @JournalEntry[SQMEPYp2Mar8av6v]{Duke Brynich von Aschaffenberg}, @JournalEntry[nrtWBzb0JITz0WkM]{Markgraf Harald von Schluessel} and @JournalEntry[FbCLcSFFVaZq9CSW]{Steward Rudolf von Trocheim}.</p>\n<p>Nearby states contributed to the mustering, including @JournalEntry[f3m8mOvHLTjuoUnD]{Hupeberg}, @JournalEntry[mDwaCu4nzY0wHVWY]{Hopfberg}, @JournalEntry[eFOFM7fsXgfThWnV]{Bohrn}, @JournalEntry[AhL154uxwRaa2157]{Lilahalle}, @JournalEntry[kM7fxZ6phqDwzkzU]{Falkenhayn} and @JournalEntry[PdheVmF2HqhLo6pi]{Haalstein}.</p>\n<p>The Jungfreud's liege, the aging @JournalEntry[ScQ0kGeaEJvqLpqU]{Viktor von Walfen} requested aid from his neighbour @JournalEntry[gqW9nV7fbB2iPhUt]{Graf Ferdinand von Wallenstein} and rode at once to Widow's Vale with the garrison of Walfenschloss.</p>\n<h4><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\" src=\"Images/Illustrations/book-illustrations/reikland-war.webp\" width=\"400\" height=\"554\" /></h4>\n<p> </p>\n<p>In the meantime, Waaagh! 'Eadbanger began to siege Grunwacht, the largest town in Widow's Vale.</p>\n<p>Despite being outnumbered, the assembled Ubersreik commanders decided they could not wait any longer for reinforcements from the Wallensteins and readied their troops to relieve Grunwacht.</p>\n<p>In order to make up for their numerical disadvantage, the council of war planned to split the greenskin forces by striking a small portion of the besieging army with the forces of the Jungfreuds, Bruners and Aschaffenbergs. If the greenskins decided to retaliate, they would be forced to leave behind some of their army to contain Grunwacht or risk exposing their rear to the soldiers contained in the town. This would allow the Ubersreik army to bring their entire force to bear on a single part of the greenskin's army and defeat them in detail.</p>\n<p>The initial attack went far better than expected when communication failures in the greenskin ranks left half of their formation guarding their artillery while the other half pursued the Ubersreik army and was destroyed.</p>\n<p>This success was short-lived however, as the bulk of the greenskin army began to move and the battle began in earnest.</p>\n<p>Unbeknownst to the Ubersreik army, the Wallensteins had not been idle. On receiving von Walfen's message, they sent messengers at once to Grunberg, where they knew that the Emperor Karl-Franz was currently conducting exercises with the Third Reikland State Regiment. Instead of marching their troops south to Ubersreik immediately, they readied river transportation and waited for the State Army.</p>\n<p>At Widow's Vale, the fighting was savage. While the Ubersreik forces were taking heavy losses, the greenskins were taking the worst of it. Though outnumbered, von Jungfreud's army was gradually gaining the upper hand and morale was high.</p>\n<p>When the State Army and the Wallensteins arrived at Ubersreik they were alarmed to discover that the Ubersreik army had already marched to Widow's Vale. Sailing to Traisburg, the Emperor commanded all the cavalry to disembark and ride with all haste to Grunwacht to meet with Ubersreik forces.</p>\n<p>When they arrived at Grunwacht they found the battle in progress, and fell upon the rear of the already-wavering greenskin formation. The bulk of the army was crushed between the Ubersreik anvil and the hammer of the Imperial troops, spearheaded by the Emperor astride his Griffon Deathclaw, the Reiksguard Knights and the Knights of Sturmdunkel.</p>\n<h3><img style=\"display:block;border:0px solid black;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto\" src=\"Images/Illustrations/book-illustrations/orc-battle.webp\" width=\"650\" height=\"171\" /></h3>\n<p>A young @JournalEntry[55LRxe4TiHVoNlo4]{Captain Gregor Schadelfaust} was given command of the soldiers tasked with relieving the siege of Grunwacht. This he did with such success that his company pursued the fleeing besiegers into the right flank of the main greenskin force, starting a mass rout which caused the Waaagh! to rapidly crumble. For this decisive action, Schadelfaust was knighted on the battlefield. When the Emperor discovered that the local von Saal line was extinct and that Widow's Vale was merely governed by the Jungfreuds, he declared that the land be given to Schadelfaust as saviour of Widow's Vale.</p>\n<h1>Disposition of Troops</h1>\n<h3>Commanders</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Sigismund von Jungfreud the Elder</li>\n<li>Hild von Jungfreud</li>\n<li>Rudolf von Trocheim</li>\n<li>Steirlich von Bruner</li>\n<li>Brynich von Aschaffenberg</li>\n<li>Viktor von Walfen</li>\n</ul>\n<p>(Company ~200 Men)</p>\n<h3>Jungfreud Army</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Jungfreud - 10 Companies</li>\n<li>Trocheim - 2 Companies</li>\n<li>Aschaffenberg - 2 Companies</li>\n<li>Bruners - 3 Companies</li>\n<li>Schluessel - 1 Company</li>\n<li>Walfen - 1 Company</li>\n<li>Hupeberg - 2 Companies</li>\n<li>Hopfberg, Bohrn, Haalstein, Falkenhayn, Lilahalle - 5 Companies</li>\n<li>Total: 26 Companies, ~5200 Men</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Waaagh! Ghizbak</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Goblins - ~22 Companies</li>\n<li>Orcs - ~15 Companies</li>\n<li>Trolls - ~1 Company</li>\n<li>Total: 38 Companies, ~7600 Greenskins</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Wallenstein and the State Army</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Wallenstein - 6 Companies</li>\n<li>Colbesfeld - 1 Company</li>\n<li>Oberwald - 2 Companies</li>\n<li>Hammastrat - 2 Companies</li>\n<li>Third Reikland State Regiment - 10 Companies</li>\n<li>Total: 21 Companies, ~4200 Men</li>\n</ul>","img":"Images/Illustrations/book-illustrations/orc-battle.webp","folder":"3D5AeQXPQFECRFtw","sort":1100001,"permission":{"default":2,"hNHeJbKl47AOkoOO":3},"flags":{}}
{"_id":"nTDrsYU3XxCNHehO","name":"Karak Azgaraz","permission":{"default":0,"hNHeJbKl47AOkoOO":3},"folder":"0MIpj7xvY6NEdtss","sort":100000,"flags":{},"content":"<h3>Entry to the Kingdom</h3>\n<p>Individuals who have business with the Dwarf Hold must first secure a writ of passage.<br />Runescribes at the points of entry (Azgaraz Trading Post and Migdhal Skarrenruf ) require the names, place of origin, and business for all outsiders crossing into the kingdom. That information is then etched into a book with thin copper sheets to make a permanent record before the runescribe prepares a writ of passage (in Reikspiel with a few notations in Khazalid runes) for the leader of the expedition.</p>\n<p>Runescribe Fimbur Zamnilsson, the Dwarf who issues writs of passage, is a vindictive bureaucrat who is not beyond administering his own revenge should he feel he has been disrespected. He adds a Khazalid rune to the writ to ensure that Dwarf rangers checking the writ put the offender and their party through a gruelling, thorough, and embarrassing inspection.&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Azgaraz Trading Post and Merchant Pass (Vithang Kadrin)</h3>\n<p>In an effort to limit traffic on the King&rsquo;s Highway as well as solidify King Thuringar&rsquo;s land grab, the Dwarfs built Azgaraz Trading Post within Merchant Pass. The gap&rsquo;s ridges created a natural gateway of several hundred yards. The trading post is a place where Dwarf and Imperial traders can safely conduct their business. The fortified compound houses a garrison of eight and a runescribe. All guests at the compound are expected to assist in its defence should Orcs and Goblins attack.</p>\n<p>Owned and run by the Gertunmalz Brewer Clan, the Inn of the Six Pints is located within the trading post. It provides private rooms for up to sixteen people, a dormitory which can sleep up to twelve, and a stable yard for up to six beasts and four wagons.<br />Grum Dorinsson is the current master brewer and Friga, his wife, the innkeeper and chief cook. The inn&rsquo;s main dish is roasted goat covered in a spicy mustard and turnips served with a hearty, reddish-coloured malted beer called &lsquo;Dragon Breath&rsquo;.&nbsp;</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Graf von Jungfreud has sent a missive to Dwarf king Thuringar in order to apprise the Karak Dwarfs of the situation in Ubersreik and ask for the king&rsquo;s support (or failing that, neutrality). The graf&rsquo;s opponents seek to stop the correspondence. Needless to say, the Dwarfs would be less than pleased to see a fight over a letter at the trading post.&nbsp;</p>\n</blockquote>\n<h3>King's Highway</h3>\n<p>Staying on the King&rsquo;s Highway or any other dwarf road is the easiest way to travel. The Dwarfs have even built sizable stone shelters every two miles. These shelters are roughly 12 feet long and 6 feet wide with three 6-foot-tall walls. Travellers are free to use these structures to camp for the night or avoid getting drenched in a sudden downpour. The waystations often attract hungry Trolls, however.</p>\n<h3>Inn of the Silver Cross</h3>\n<p>@JournalEntry[mIAcyK8FIDvfYFMl]{Inn of the Silver Cross - Illustration}</p>\n<p>The fortified Inn of the Silver Cross is located roughly a day&rsquo;s journey from the trading post, positioned at the crossroads of the King&rsquo;s Highway and two other dwarf roads heading to the north and west. The accommodations at the inn are roughly the same as those of the Inn of the Six Pints. The clientele are mostly Dwarf farmers who grow mountain hops and barley for brewing and wheat for making bread along the northern shores of Copper Tarn. Dwarf rangers and herders of the long-haired mountain cattle are also found stopping by the inn.<br />The taproom is run by Vikram and Karga Svensson of the Gertunmalz Brewer Clan. The Svenssons brew a dark-coloured, filling lager (&lsquo;Valaya&rsquo;s Cure&rsquo;) and an amber-coloured wheat beer (&lsquo;Golden Tears&rsquo;). Beef is generally the meat of choice at the inn, served with a white, fragrant hard cheese and buttered bread.<br />The grain comes from a nearby mill on River Turquoise (Ruvalk Teikal).&nbsp;</p>\n<h3>Entering Karak Azgaraz</h3>\n<p>@JournalEntry[k334HhS52E276BGp]{Ancestor's Gate - Illustration}</p>\n<p>The main road from the Azgaraz Trading Post passes between Copper Tarn and Eyrie Peak before continuing deep into the mountains, where it eventually enters Bretonnia. A side road, marked by statues of Dwarf sentries, winds its way up the mountain. Watchtowers made from granite blocks are located so that the road and those travelling it are always in view by one tower or another. The road zigzags until it reaches a huge 50-foot brass gate two - thirds of the way up the western face of the mountain. Two gigantic statues of powerful Dwarfs flank the immense gate: one of Grungni and the other Grimnir. Known as the Ancestors&rsquo; Gate, the imposing gate is operated by a system of clockwork gears, only opening when the king or other royalty enter or leave the Dwarf Hold. A side-door allows less important folk to enter. This common entrance is protected by murder holes and a crack unit of guards armed with crossbows.</p>\n<h3>Skadi Scowlbrow</h3>\n<p>New arrivals are greeted in the atrium by an &lsquo;Overseer&rsquo;, an official guide who ensures that they are never left unaccompanied. Dwarfs dislike strangers prying into their aff airs- their hold has not endured for so long by being open to everyone&rsquo;s inspection.</p>\n<p>Skadi is an especially suspicious fellow, making him perfect for the job, though a very unpleasant companion.</p>"}
{"_id":"nWqFBMH8iDBs2yuO","name":"The Basement","permission":{"default":0,"2Hruae7FTjv0sSwL":3,"hNHeJbKl47AOkoOO":3},"folder":"pdvIHQsjlpM0hC2f","sort":200000,"flags":{},"content":"<p>If the Characters enter the basement during daylight hours, there is a 10% chance she is currently on the hunt through the building&rsquo;s crawl space, otherwise she is huddled in a corner behind stacks of old laundry and mattresses. If the Characters enter at night, Melone is not present, and is instead off somewhere feeding, to return come sunrise.</p>\n<p>To determine where the Vampire is in the maze, the Characters will be required to perform a <strong>Very Hard (&minus;30) Track Test</strong>. <em>(GM Note: Could start at Daunting (-40))</em></p>\n<p>If the group is working together, they perform only a single Test, gaining additional Tests only if they split up (and therefore, suffering more consequences).</p>\n<ul>\n<li>On a success, move to The Vampire&rsquo;s Lair.&nbsp;</li>\n<li>Failure means the Characters continue to stumble through the maze and must roll 1d100 on the Maze Encounters Table, adding +10 to the result per &minus;SL.\n<ul>\n<li>@RollTable[GiXQst9Puq1faFFJ]{Maze Encounters Table}&nbsp;</li>\n<li>After every failed Test, the Test must be repeated, but at a cumulative +10.&nbsp;</li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n<p>If there is ever a question over which Character suffers the effects of an encounter, either determine the target randomly or use the Character with the lowest score in the associated Skill or Characteristic. Example: Loose Nail would target the Character with the lowest Perception Skill.</p>\n<p>Additionally, if Melone is present, she can perform an <strong>Easy (+40) Perception Test each Round</strong> the Characters spend in the maze. If the Characters are specifically choosing to be stealthy, the Character with the lowest Stealth Skill in the group may make this an Opposed Test.</p>\n<ul>\n<li>If Melone succeeds on her Perception Test, she will wait until the party is in an inopportune position and will ambush them. However, it takes her as many Rounds as the &minus;SL of the last Track Test (as the Characters are far away from her, and she must reach them herself through the maze, or along the ceiling).</li>\n</ul>"}
